In fact, the most typical thing in contemporary Asturian folk music is precisely that the gaita has its own solo and that it also appears only in the instrumental parts where there is no voice

content_translation: It makes me sad to return to Malaga and see what is there after having spent a few days in Oviedo. content_translation:
EDP and Central Lechera Asturiana renew their agreement to promote energy self-consumption.- OVIEDO, 3 May. (EUROPA PRESS) -

The farmers of Central Lechera Asturiana who have built a solar installation with EDP are self-consuming more than 64% of the energy produced, which translates into an estimated average savings higher than when Central Lechera Asturiana and EDP began to promote self-consumption of energy among the nearly 1,000 members of the cooperative. La industria asturiana vuelve a tasas positivas tras seis meses de caÃ­da .- La producciÃ³n industrial asturiana volviÃ³ a crecer en marzo por vez primera en seis meses en tasa anual, pese a que la producciÃ³n energÃ©tica se contrajo el 22,2%, y se situÃ³ por encima del promedio nacional, con un incremento del 6% respecto al mismo mes del ejercicio anterior, siete dÃ©cimas por encima del incremento promedio nacional (5,3%), segÃºn el Instituto Nacional de EstadÃ­stica (INE). 
 
 Se trata, en todo caso, de una recuperaciÃ³n aÃºn discreta. ocupa la dÃ©cima posiciÃ³n regional por progresiÃ³n industrial, despuÃ©s de que en buena parte de 2021 y algunos meses de 2022 hubiese protagonizado una contundente remontada poscovid, con incrementos interanuales de doble dÃ­gito que llegaron a alcanzar en algÃºn caso el 60,4% respecto al mismo mes del aÃ±o anterior.
content_translation:
The Asturian industry returns to positive rates after six months of decline .- Asturian industrial production grew again in March for the first time in six months at an annual rate, despite the fact that energy production contracted by 22.2%, and was above the national average, with an increase of 6% compared to the same month of the previous year, seven tenths above the national average increase (5.3%), according to the National Institute of Statistics (INE). 
 
 In any case, this is a recovery that is still discrete. It ranks tenth in the region by industrial progression, after a large part of 2021 and some months of 2022 it had a strong post-Covid comeback, with year-on-year double-digit increases that in some cases reached 60.4% compared to the same month of the previous year.

La producciÃ³n de la industria asturiana cae un 3,4 % en el primer trimestre .- Planta de galvanizado de ArcelorMittal en AvilÃ©s, en una imagen de archivo. EFE/J.L.Cereijido.
 
Oviedo (EFE).- La producciÃ³n de la industria asturiana cayÃ³ en febrero un 2 por ciento en tasa interanual, con lo que en el acumulado del primer trimestre ha descendido un 3,4 por ciento en relaciÃ³n al mismo periodo del aÃ±o pasado debido en buena parte a la averÃ­a en uno de los hornos de ArcelorMittal, segÃºn el Ã­ndice elaborado por la Sociedad Asturiana de Estudios EconÃ³micos e Industriales (Sadei).
 
En su informe,Â SadeiÂ apunta que la industria regional redujo su cota productiva en marzo, en contraste con el repunte del 0,2 por ciento de febrero que puso fin a cinco meses consecutivos de descensos, 'muy condicionada por algunos imprevistos que retrasan, de nuevo, una hipotÃ©tica recuperaciÃ³n'.
content_translation:
The production of the Asturian industry fell by 3.4% in the first quarter .- ArcelorMittal galvanizing plant in AvilÃ©s, in a file image. EFE/J.L. Cereijido.
 
Oviedo (EFE) .- The production of the Asturian industry fell by 2 percent year-on-year in February, which in the cumulative rate of the first quarter it fell by 3.4 percent compared to the same period last year, largely due to the breakdown in one of the ArcelorMittal kilns, according to the index prepared by the Asturian Society for Economic and Industrial Studies (Sadei).
 
In her report, Sadei points out that the regional industry reduced its production level in March, in contrast to the 0.2 percent increase in February, which ended five consecutive months of declines, 'heavily conditioned by some unforeseen events that delay, once again, a hypothetical recovery'.
